political histories to bear on contemporary debates ranging from its role in relation to the politics of white supremacy to the digital harvesting of habits in practices of algorithmic governance. Throughout, Bennett tracks how habit’s repetitions have been articulated differently across divisions of class, race, and gender, demonstrating that although habit serves as an apparatus for achieving success, self-fulfillment, and freedom for the powerful, it has simultaneously served as a means of control over women, racialized peoples, and subordinate classes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aHabitxPolitical aspects. 0aHabitxSocial aspects. 0aPolitical culture. 0aPolitical socialization. 0aPolitical sociology. 0aPolitics and culture. 0aPower (Philosophy) 0aPower (Philosophy). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Social Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027331?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027331423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027331/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles